## The Update Cycle of Grief

Windows Update is not a feature. It is a lifestyle. It is a commitment. It is a relationship you never consented to but cannot leave. It operates on its own timeline, its own schedule, and its own definition of "convenient."

### Stage 1: Denial

A small notification appears: "Updates are available." You dismiss it. Not now. You're busy. You have work. You have a meeting in 5 minutes. You have a life.

Windows Update does not care about your life.

### Stage 2: Bargaining

"Restart now or schedule for later?" You click "Later." You schedule it for 3 AM. This is the deal. The agreement. The social contract between you and your operating system. You agreed to 3 AM. Surely that's the end of it. Surely.

### Stage 3: Anger

It is 2:47 PM on a Tuesday. You are in the middle of an unsaved Excel spreadsheet. 47 rows of data. Two hours of work. Your screen goes blue. Not BSOD blue. WORSE. Update blue. "Working on updates. 12% complete. Don't turn off your computer."

DON'T TURN OFF YOUR COMPUTER? I DIDN'T TURN IT ON TO UPDATE. I TURNED IT ON TO USE. THESE ARE DIFFERENT ACTIVITIES. ONE IS PRODUCTIVE. THE OTHER IS MICROSOFT REARRANGING MY REGISTRY KEYS WITHOUT ASKING.

"But I scheduled it for 3 AM—"

Windows Update does not honor the social contract. Windows Update is an anarchist.

### Stage 4: Depression

The update takes 45 minutes. Your meeting started 40 minutes ago. You are staring at "87% complete" and it has been 87% for 20 minutes. The progress bar is a lie. The percentage is a suggestion. The ETA is a fiction. Time has no meaning. Only the update exists.

Your colleagues are in the meeting without you. They assume you're dead. They are not entirely wrong.

### Stage 5: Acceptance

The desktop returns. Everything looks the same. Nothing has changed. Wait — the taskbar is centered now. The right-click menu has been "simplified." Your default browser has been reset to Edge. The Start menu has new "suggestions." These suggestions are ads. The update added ads. You waited 45 minutes. For ads.

Your Excel spreadsheet is gone. AutoRecover has a version from 2 hours ago. The 47 rows are 12 rows. The two hours of work are 0 hours of work. Windows Update has taken your data, your time, your browser preference, and your will to continue.

This happens every month. Sometimes twice. Until you die or switch to Linux. Whichever comes first.

### Bonus Stage: The Feature Update

Twice a year, Microsoft ships a "Feature Update." This is a 4GB download that takes 2 hours to install, reboots your computer 3 times, resets 17 of your preferences, re-enables 5 telemetry services you disabled, reinstalls Edge, reinstalls OneDrive, reinstalls Candy Crush, and adds one (1) new feature: a slightly different emoji picker.

The emoji picker is worse than the old one.

