## The Start Menu: A Love Story Gone Wrong

### Windows XP (2001): The Golden Age

The Start menu was simple. Programs on the left. Utilities on the right. Start button on the bottom left. Click it. See your stuff. Use your stuff. Close it. The end.

It was beautiful. It was functional. It was the last time anyone at Microsoft was allowed to make a UI decision without a 47-slide PowerPoint presentation about "engagement metrics."

### Windows Vista (2007): The First Warning Sign

They made it translucent. Glass effects everywhere. Your GPU is now rendering a Start menu at 60fps. The Start menu consumes more VRAM than some games. But it looks pretty. This is fine. We're fine. (This is when it started. This is when the rot set in.)

### Windows 8 (2012): The Crime

They removed the Start menu.

Let me say that again.

They. Removed. The Start menu.

The single most recognized UI element in computing history. The thing that has been in the bottom-left corner of every Windows computer since 1995. The thing that every human on Earth between the ages of 5 and 95 knows how to use. They REMOVED it. And replaced it with a FULL-SCREEN app launcher. With LIVE TILES. On a DESKTOP. With a MOUSE.

Someone at Microsoft looked at an iPad, looked at a desktop PC, and said "these are the same thing." And everyone in the room nodded. And Windows 8 shipped. And 1.5 billion desktop users stared at a touch-optimized full-screen app launcher with a mouse and keyboard and wondered what they did to deserve this.

The Start menu was reinstated two years later in Windows 8.1 after what I can only assume was an intervention staged by every PC user on the planet.

### Windows 10 (2015): The Compromise Nobody Asked For

Live Tiles + traditional list. A hybrid. A chimera. A horse designed by a committee that resulted in a camel. But also the camel has ads. "Suggested apps" in the Start menu. On a $200 OS. The suggestions are Candy Crush. The suggestions are always Candy Crush.

### Windows 11 (2021): The Art Project

They moved it to the CENTER. The Start button. The one that has been in the BOTTOM LEFT for 26 YEARS. They put it in the CENTER. Like a MacOS dock. Except worse. Because it's Windows. And the Start menu is now a floating rounded-corner panel with "Pinned" apps on top and "Recommended" on the bottom. The "Recommended" section shows files you opened recently. And ads. Always ads.

You cannot resize it. You cannot move it. You cannot add groups. You cannot add folders. Features that existed in WINDOWS 10. One version ago. REMOVED. Not deprecated. Not moved. REMOVED. Because someone at Microsoft saw a clean UI mockup and said "this looks nice" and shipped it without checking if any of the features still worked.

The Start menu is no longer a tool. It is a billboard with a search bar.

