## Settings vs. Control Panel: A Civil War

In Windows 11, there are two places to change settings:

1. **Settings** — The new one. Pretty. Minimal. Missing 60% of the options.
2. **Control Panel** — The old one. Ugly. Comprehensive. Microsoft has been trying to kill it since 2015. It refuses to die. Like Edge. But useful.

Need to change your display settings? Settings app.
Need to change advanced display settings? Control Panel.
Need to change network settings? Settings app.
Need to change adapter settings? Control Panel.
Need to change sound settings? Settings app.
Need to change per-application audio routing? A third app (Volume Mixer) that opens from the taskbar but looks different from both Settings and Control Panel.
Need to change mouse settings? Settings app.
Need to change mouse DPI? Control Panel.
Need to change mouse pointer? Settings app for color, Control Panel for custom icons, THIRD PARTY APP for actual functionality.

Microsoft has been "migrating" settings from Control Panel to the Settings app for 11 years. They are 40% done. At this rate, they will finish in 2042. My grandchildren will inherit the Control Panel. They will not know what it is. They will open it. They will see checkboxes and dropdown menus and tabs. They will weep with confusion. Or nostalgia. Or both.

The two apps sometimes link to each other. "Advanced settings" in the Settings app opens Control Panel. "Go to Settings" in Control Panel opens the Settings app. They are in a relationship. It is toxic. They cannot live with each other. They cannot live without each other. They are Settings and Control Panel. And they are BOTH on your computer. Using DIFFERENT design languages. With DIFFERENT navigation systems. For the SAME operating system.

This is Microsoft's idea of a unified experience.

