## The Telemetry: They're Always Watching

Windows collects telemetry data. This is a fact. It is in the EULA. The EULA that nobody reads because it is 19,000 words long. That's longer than "The Great Gatsby." You have to read a novel-length legal document to find out that your computer is sending data to Microsoft. And even after you read it, you can't opt out. You can reduce it. To "Basic." But "Basic" still sends:

- Hardware information
- Device configuration
- Software inventory
- Crash data
- Performance data
- "Connectivity data" (WHAT connections you make. WHERE you connect. WHEN.)
- "Browsing data" (IF you use Edge. Which you don't. But they check.)

"Full" telemetry adds:
- Inking and typing data (WHAT YOU TYPE.)
- App usage data (WHICH APPS YOU USE. HOW LONG. HOW OFTEN.)
- Browser history (yes, really)
- Enhanced error reports (a screenshot of what you were doing when the error occurred)

There is no "None." There is no "Off." There is no "I paid $200 please stop watching me." The slider goes from "Some surveillance" to "All surveillance." There is no "No surveillance." The absence of "No surveillance" IS the surveillance.

The services responsible for this include:
- `DiagTrack` (Connected User Experiences and Telemetry — 15 words to say "we watch you")
- `dmwappushservice` (WAP Push Message Routing — yes, WAP, like it's 2003, like we're sending MMS, like we're using a RAZR flip phone)
- `DcpSvc` (Data Collection Publishing Service — the name contains "DATA COLLECTION." THEY NAMED IT DATA COLLECTION.)
- `WerSvc` (Windows Error Reporting — "your app crashed, here's everything you were doing")
- `PcaSvc` (Program Compatibility Assistant — "you ran an old program, we're telling Microsoft")
- 25+ more services. Running. Right now. On YOUR computer.

WISO disables all of them. Because we believe your computer should work for YOU. Not for Microsoft's quarterly earnings report.

