## The Registry: Dante's Inferno

The Windows Registry is where settings go to die.

It is a hierarchical database. With 5 root keys. Containing approximately 4 million subkeys. On a fresh install. FOUR MILLION. Each key can have multiple values. Each value can be a string, a number, a binary blob, or a cry for help.

The Registry was designed in 1992. It has not been fundamentally redesigned since. It is a 34-year-old database. That runs the most popular operating system on Earth. That stores everything from your wallpaper preference to your network configuration to whether the taskbar is centered or left-aligned. IN ONE DATABASE. WITH NO SCHEMA. NO DOCUMENTATION. NO TYPES. NO VALIDATION.

You want to disable Cortana? Registry key.
You want to remove ads from the Start menu? Registry key.
You want to disable telemetry? 14 registry keys. In 6 different locations. Under 3 different root keys.
You want to change the right-click menu back to the old one? Registry key.
You want to make your computer YOUR computer? 50+ registry keys. Scattered across the hive like Easter eggs hidden by someone who WANTS them to stay hidden.

The Registry Editor (`regedit.exe`) has not been meaningfully updated since Windows XP. It looks the same as it did in 2001. In 2001, we were using CRT monitors and dial-up internet. The Registry Editor does not know we've moved on. It is frozen in time. Like a bug in amber. Like Microsoft's commitment to a single settings interface.

Every WISO build modifies 50+ registry keys. We know where they are because the developer spent 3 weeks mapping them. At night. By candlelight. (The power went out. The coffee maker was on the UPS. Priorities.) The raccoons navigated the registry by instinct. Gary found a Cortana key. Linda found a telemetry key. Steve found a key from Windows Vista that nobody knows what it does. We left it there. Out of respect. And fear.

