## Printer Setup: A Lovecraftian Horror

There are things in this world that humans were not meant to understand. The nature of consciousness. The origin of the universe. Why Windows printer drivers need 500MB of disk space to make a piece of paper have ink on it.

### The Setup Process

1. Plug in printer. Windows: "Setting up your device!" (This will take somewhere between 30 seconds and 45 minutes. There is no way to predict which.)
2. Windows searches for drivers. On Windows Update. Which requires internet. To install a printer. That is connected via USB. Physically. With a cable. That is carrying data. Data that could include the driver. But doesn't. Because the driver is in the cloud. For a printer. Connected by a CABLE.
3. The driver is 487MB. For a printer. A PRINTER. A device that puts ink on paper. The driver is HALF A GIGABYTE. My first hard drive was 500MB. The ENTIRE HARD DRIVE was the same size as this PRINTER DRIVER.
4. Installation requires a reboot. For a printer. I need to RESTART MY COMPUTER. To use a PERIPHERAL DEVICE. That puts INK on PAPER.
5. After reboot, the printer "works." Quotes because "works" in the context of Windows printing means "functions approximately 73% of the time, with the remaining 27% distributed between 'offline' (while plugged in), 'error' (with no error message), and 'needs attention' (with no indication of what attention)."
6. The printer manufacturer's software ALSO installed. A separate application. With a taskbar icon. A startup entry. A background service. A notification center integration. And a "special offers" tab. For a PRINTER. The printer has a DEALS SECTION. I am being marketed to. BY A PRINTER.

### The Error

And then the printer goes "offline." While plugged in. While turned on. While printing. Mid-page. The printer goes OFFLINE. DURING a print job. And Windows says "Printer offline." And you look at the printer. And the printer is ON. Its lights are GREEN. It is HUMMING. It is READY. But Windows says it's offline. So it's offline. Because Windows said so. Because reality is whatever Windows says it is.

You restart the print spooler. You remove and re-add the printer. You update the driver. You uninstall and reinstall. You check the connection. You cry. You check the connection again. You restart the computer. You restart the printer. You restart your career ambitions. Nothing works. And then, randomly, 45 minutes later, the printer starts working again. With no explanation. No logs. No diagnostic information. Just: offline, offline, offline, printing.

HP printers are worse. But that's not Microsoft's fault. That's HP's fault. Some tortures are collaborative.

