## File Explorer: A Museum of Compromise

File Explorer in Windows 11 is a museum. It contains artifacts from every era of Windows:

- The address bar: Windows Vista (2007)
- The navigation pane: Windows 7 (2009)
- The ribbon (now removed): Windows 8 (2012)
- The simplified toolbar: Windows 11 (2021)
- The right-click menu: Windows 11 (simplified, hiding all the useful options behind "Show more options" which opens the WINDOWS 10 right-click menu, meaning BOTH menus exist, one INSIDE the other, like a UI MATRYOSHKA DOLL)
- The file properties dialog: Windows 95 (1995). I am not joking. Open a file's properties. Look at the tabs. Look at the checkboxes. Look at the font. That dialog has not been redesigned in 31 YEARS.

File Explorer also now has:
- A OneDrive section (that you can't remove without registry editing)
- A "Gallery" section (that you didn't ask for)
- Tabs (took them 30 years but they did it, and only 20 years after every other file manager)
- A search bar that searches Bing before searching your own files (WE COVERED THIS)

The "Quick Access" feature pins frequently used folders. Except it also pins recently opened files. Which means your colleagues can see what files you opened recently. Which is either a privacy concern or a vulnerability or both. Depends on what you opened. And whether your colleagues are looking. They are. They always are. Just like Microsoft.

