## The Taskbar: Microsoft's Art Project

The Windows 11 taskbar is centered. After 26 years of being left-aligned. You can move it back to the left. You cannot move it to the top, bottom, or sides. Features that existed in Windows 10. Removed. Because aesthetics are more important than functionality at Microsoft. Form follows function, except at Microsoft, where form follows a designer's Dribbble portfolio.

The taskbar cannot be resized. In Windows 10, you could make it taller. In Windows 11, you cannot. You get one size. Microsoft's size. Which is either too big for people who want screen space or too small for people who want touch targets. It is the wrong size for everyone. This is called "design."

The taskbar cannot display labels. Only icons. You have 15 Chrome windows open. They are all the same icon. Which one is your email? Which one is your work? Which one is the one with 47 tabs that you're afraid to close because ONE of them is important but you can't remember which? You don't know. The taskbar doesn't know. Microsoft doesn't know. Nobody knows. We are all lost. In a sea of identical icons. On a taskbar we can't customize.

The clock used to show seconds. Now it doesn't. You can re-enable it. In the registry. Because of COURSE the clock seconds setting is in the REGISTRY. Where else would it be? In Settings? Don't be absurd. Settings is for things like "change your wallpaper" and "connect to Wi-Fi." The clock? The CLOCK is a REGISTRY setting. Obviously.

