## Stockholm Syndrome: Why We Stay

You've read 400+ lines about how Windows tortures us. You're probably thinking: "Why don't you just use Linux?"

Here's why:

1. **Games.** 99% of PC games are built for Windows. DirectX is Windows-only. Proton and Wine are getting better but "getting better" is not "works perfectly." When I'm trying to game at midnight, I don't want to spend 3 hours configuring wine prefixes and Vulkan layers. I want to click "Play." On Windows. Which has Candy Crush. But also has my games. We contain contradictions.

2. **Adobe.** Photoshop. Premiere. After Effects. The creative industry standard. Linux has GIMP. GIMP is free. GIMP is also named GIMP. The name alone costs it 50% of its potential users. Adobe does not run on Linux. Adobe will never run on Linux. Adobe can barely run on Windows.

3. **Hardware.** Every driver works on Windows. Every peripheral. Every monitor. Every printer (barely). Every webcam. Every drawing tablet. Linux driver support is "you might get lucky, or you might spend 6 hours compiling a kernel module and then your Wi-Fi stops working."

4. **Work.** Your company uses Microsoft 365. Your company uses Active Directory. Your company uses Outlook. Your IT department says "we support Windows." They do not say "we support Linux." If you install Linux and something breaks, IT says "we don't support that." And they're right. And you're alone. With a terminal. And a broken Wi-Fi driver.

5. **Familiarity.** We grew up with Windows. We know where things are. (Except in the Settings app, where things move every update.) We know the keyboard shortcuts. We know the quirks. We know that Alt+F4 closes a window and that Ctrl+Alt+Del opens the security screen and that the Start menu is in the bottom left unless it's Windows 11 in which case it's in the center because Microsoft went through a PHASE.

So we stay. We stay with the ads and the telemetry and the Candy Crush and the forced updates and the Edge nagging and the OneDrive popups and the OOBE hostage negotiation. We stay because the alternatives are worse. Or different. Or require effort. And we are tired. Because Windows Update rebooted our computer during the night and our sleep was interrupted by a reboot notification sound that we thought we disabled but apparently didn't because the setting was reset by a Feature Update.

This is why WISO exists.

Not to replace Windows. Not to fight Microsoft. (OK, a little to fight Microsoft.)

But to make Windows what it should have been all along: an operating system. That operates. The system. Without ads. Without bloat. Without surveillance. Without Candy Crush.

Just Windows. Clean. Fast. Private. Yours.

